---
title: "Strengthening the Global Semiconductor Supply Chain in an Uncertain Era"
author: "Antonio Varas, Raj Varadarajan, Jimmy Goodrich, Falan Yinug"
domain: "semiconductors.org"
url: "https://www.semiconductors.org/strengthening-the-global-semiconductor-supply-chain-in-an-uncertain-era/"
pubDate: 2021-12-10
takeaway: "A highly cited joint report by BCG and SIA assessing supply chain vulnerabilities and highlighting the extreme geographic concentration of advanced semiconductor manufacturing in East Asia."
---

The BCG and SIA report on the semiconductor supply chain makes it impossible to look at our infrastructure the same way. It is one thing to know that microchips are hard to make; it is another to realize that the most advanced semiconductor manufacturing is concentrated in a tiny geographic sliver in East Asia. As someone building a technology company, I realize that our entire business is indirectly leveraged on this extreme geographic single point of failure. If anything goes sideways there, the downstream effects on global server capacity and consumer devices will be immediate and catastrophic.

What stands out to me is how the globalized efficiency we spent decades optimizing has come at the expense of systemic robustness. In our race to reduce unit costs, we’ve created a house of cards where no single nation holds all the pieces to the puzzle. Rebuilding domestic manufacturing capability or diversifying geographic nodes is a massive, multi-decade undertaking. We cannot just write off this risk; we need to actively consider hardware diversity, edge capabilities, and how our software architectures can survive in an environment where hardware availability becomes highly variable.

### What stuck with me
* **Extreme geographic concentration**: The world relies on a handful of highly vulnerable manufacturing hubs in East Asia for almost all advanced logic chips.
* **Efficiency versus resilience**: Decades of optimizing for low costs have stripped the global semiconductor ecosystem of necessary fallback options.
* **Decade-scale rebuilds**: Diversifying manufacturing capacity and developing new domestic fabs require tens of billions of dollars and years of sustained effort.
